Note that this rating system is a direct consequence of the __Italian scholastic grading__ system. Therefore I'm not trying to convert the scores in a "real" 0 to 10 system: my head can't stand up to that. I understand that this practically fu**s the entire mean score system of anilist, but I don't care. Già il rapporto tra Killua e Gon era tanta roba, ma sono riusciti a crearne un'altro allo stesso livello. Anche qui personaggi top tier. Ha un vibe molto più dark rispetto al resto (ma anche prevedibile, continuava ad essere ripetuto che Gon poteva diventare un mostro). Ha un ritmo decisamente più lento rispetto al resto, che ci sta anche, visto che introduce diversi spunti di riflessione, primo tra tutti:
"With using the nuke, Netero put Meruem and all his ants in their place. The ants established themselves as a species built upon cruelty and power, but they had no idea how far ahead humanity already was at their own game. That is what Netero’s character represented in that fight. His victory wasn’t a proud, glorious triumph for winning a fight (as you said, Nen, skill and technique) from the good side, it was a reminder of how horrible the human specie can be. The foreshadowing of Gon is built throughout the series in its morality. It is shown a couple of times that he doesn't react to other people dying and only care about himself and the ones who love. He was an egoist and his moral was that twisted from the beginning: the Chimera Ant arc just gave him an opportunity to show how cruel he could be. And the execution's greatness lies in the fact that Gon at first is seen as an innocent human being but then turns into a monster, in the other side, Meruem who's born a monster get its redemption by discovering his human side." ~@Tumultuoso
